You are building a small, self-contained web application called Toolsgen - an AI-Powered Internal 
Tools Builder.

Non-technical team members describe a tool they need in plain English; the app uses the
@openai/codex-sdk — OpenAI's official TypeScript/Node SDK to generate a working HTML tool,
renders it live in an iframe, and saves it to a personal library for reuse and iteration.

Produce the following files in this exact order. Do not create any file until its test file
exists and is confirmed to fail. Once it's created, run the test for that file and fix any errors. 
Once the tests for this file all pass, commit the file to git with an appropriate commit message.

tests/db.test.js
db.js
tests/codegen.test.js
codegen.js
tests/server.test.js
server.js
index.html
app.js
package.json
.env.example

The user should be able to go to the website, and login with their email and password, if the email address 
doesnt exist in the database, create the user. 

The user should see a library of tools they have created previously, they should have a button to generate
a new tool that takes them to the tool generation page, and a button to logout which ends their session.
Each Tool should have a Card including the Tool name, a truncated copy of the prompt used to generate
the tool and if the tool has been generated by the current user, an edit button that takes the user 
to the tool generation page to allow them to modify the prompt that was used to create the tool.

The tool generation page should be split into two sections - a Prompt Input and a Live Preview.

The Prompt Input should have a text area for the user to type the prompt that describes the app and a 
"Generate Tool" button that triggers the Codex codejen.js to generate a simple single page application 
with embedded javascript and css. There should be a checkbox to "Share Application" and a Publish button 
which will save the Tool to the users Library, and if the "Share Application" checkbox is checked, save
the Tool to all other Users libraries.

The Live Preview page should render the Tool in a preview iFrame so the user can see the created tool.
There should be a "Open in new tab" button that allows the tool to be opened outside of Toolgen in a new
tab.

Above the Prompt Input and Live Preview sections there should be a "Return to library" button on the 
top right of the page.



